THE PEARL
Written by John Steinbecks
THE GENERAL CONCEPT OF THE PEARL
The Novel the Pearl centers on Greed, Corruption and Obsession of various people, who
would like to possess Kinos Pearl for their own greed.
Kino too is obsessed with the Pearl that he is ready to do anything to protect the Pearl and sell it
at a fair price.
At last Kino has lost his canoe, house and son.
MAIN CAHRACTERS IN THE PEARL
1. Kino:
The protagonist of the novell (Novel). He is a simple man who lives in a brush house with his
wife, Juana and their son, Coyotito, both of whom he loves very much.
He is a young Mexican, Indian man who is satisfied with his life up until he discovers the Pearl.
His discovery of the Pearl, the people around him lead him to lose his most precious objects
such as canoe and house including his son.
2. Juana
She is Kinos wife. She shows submission and fierce will in the face of threats to her family.
When issues surrounding them twist she senses danger and advise her husband to through the
Pearl back into the sea. She describes the Pearl as evil.
True to her words the family has suffered and lost valuable possessions and in the end Kino
takes her advice and throw back the Pearl into the sea.
3. Coyotito
Kino and Juanas only son, who is stung by a scorpion while resting in a hammock one morning
Prep By Mr. E. Sam Navaya
Page 3 of 36
Because Coyotito is an infant, he is helpless to improve his situation and thus at the mercy of
those who provide for him.
Kino and Juanas efforts to save him by finding a big pearl with which they can pay a doctor
prove to be more harm than good.
4. Juan Tomas
Kinos older brother
Deeply loyal to his family
Juan Tomas supports Kino in all of his endeavors but warns him of the dangers involved in
possessing such a valuable Pearl.
5. Apolonia
Juanas Tomas wife and the mother of four children.
Like her husband, Apolonia is sympathetic to Kino and Juanas plight and she agrees to give
them shelter in their time of need.
6. The Doctor
He is corrupted by greed and racism.
He prefers to treat the rich only to the poor, his charges are too far to the normal.
The doctor initially refuses to treat Coyotito but changes his mind after learning that Kino has
found a great Pearl.
He represents the arrogance, condescension, and greed at the heart of colonial society.
7. THE PRIEST
The local priest (Village priest)
As a priest, represents moral virtues and goodness but he is just interested in exploiting Kinos
wealth as everyone else.
He hopes of finding a way to persuade Kino to give him some of the money he will make from
the Pearl.
Prep By Mr. E. Sam Navaya
Page 4 of 36
8. THE TRACKERS
The group of violent and corrupt men that follows Kino and Juana when they leave the
village, hoping to steal Kinos Pearl.
9. THE PEARL BUYER/THE BUYER
The extremely well-organized and corrupt pearl dealers in La Paz. Systematically cheat and
exploit the Indian pearl divers who sell them their goods. They desperately long to cheat
Kino out of his pearl.
SUMMARY
The Novel, which was first published in 1947 is about Kino, his wife Juana and son, Coyotito.
The son, Coyotito, is stung by a scorpion and Kino has no money for treatment.
He hunts for a pearl valuable enough to cover medical bills.
He finds a good pearl that ignites jealousy and greed among people of all walks of life.
As a result selling a pearl at fair price become difficult. He is therefore unable to pay the
medical bills.
In an attempt to go to the capital where he can sell the Pearl at a Fair price ,Coyotito is shot by a
tracker.
Kino believes his wife that the pearl is Evil. He takes is back and throws it into the sea
By this time, the Pearl has brought more trouble than wealth. He has lost his Canoe, house and
son.
THE GEOGRAPHICAL SETTING
The story is stet in La Paz Mexico. This is rural (area) fishi9ng village and the larger more
developed town of La Paz.
JUSTIFICATION
This is evidenced by the simplicity and hardship of the life of fishing village which is
constructed to the easier and more comfortable life of the town.

Kino paddle out. They pass through the Oyster bed that is littered, cracked and opened. These

Pearls are made when an Irritant; usually parasite and not the proverbial grain of sand works its
way into the Oyster, Mussel or calm.
As defense mechanism, a fluid is used to coat the irritant. Layer upon layer of this coating called
nacre, is deposited until lustrous Pearl is formed.
Kino dives to the bottom with the help of heavy rock. He manages to fill his basket with
unopened Oysters and while he hears the song of the Pearl that might be.
Kino was a well-known expert. He mages to stay under water for two full minutes looking for the
best Oysters. He gets a very big Oyster slightly opened which contains something in it. He comes
to the surface with it.
Juana noticed Kinos excitement and deliberately looks away. She believes expecting too much
drives lucky way. She advises him to open the big oyster and a valuable Pearl is found.
Juana noticed that Coyotitos swelling has gone down. The poison is leaving his body.
Kino shouts in excitement and that has made other Canoes to paddle over his boat.

PLOT
The news that has got a pearl spread the whole town of La Paz. In this time everyone in this
town is knowing that Kino is going to sell his Pearl today.
Most of the time, Pearl buyers try to outdo (compete) with one other in order to buy the pearl.
The free market in this town follows capitalism system. This system is costly for the merchants.
To avoid this costly system of capitalism, buyers meet in advance and agree on a price that is
far below the pearls actual value
Pearl divers had decided not to go to work in order to watch Kino sell his pearl. They are
waiting with excitement
Many people stand around and discuss things they would like if they had Kinos pearl. Some say
would buy world peace.
Kino and his family are dressed in their finest clothes and they are on their way to town
Kinos brother Juan Tomas had cautioned (advised) his brother not to be cheated by the buyers.
Juan Tomas also remind Kino if a story their father told them when they were young.
Other local pearl sellers have sensed that the buyers may not give them fair prices. Therefore,
have polled their pearl and sent them all with one man to the capital in a larger and more just
market.
Then Kino unwraps the pearl and looks forward to the buyers reaction. The buyers show no
reaction at all. The buyer tries to entice Kino with coin which slips and falls into his lap.
The buyer then looks at Kinos pearl and calls it Clumsy for being two big (large). He offers
thousand pesos. Kino declares that it is worth fifty thousand pesos.
The agent tells Kino to go and ask other agents independently the value of the pearl. (These
people are working together to keep the price low.)
Kino goes to the next agent who offers him six hundred. Kino quickly takes away his pearl and
declares that will go and sell it at the capital.

The family cancels the trip and returns home side by side. Kino carries the rifle while Juana

Kino hears the song of the family. He goes back to the water. All what he sees in the pearl is

The pearl looks ugly, the pearls music is destroyed.
Kino hands the pearl to Juana but she refuses. Then Kino with anger and grief, he throws the

Finally, the music of the pearl cannot be heard any more.

MAJOR THEMES IN THE PEARL
1. OBSESSION
Kino dives for pearls in attempt to find one with great value
He would like to pay the doctor for Coyotitos treatment after being stung by a
Scorpion. He gets one valuable Pearl.
Kino considers the pearl as a fulfillment of his dreams for the family. He will acquire
new clothes, conduct church wedding with his wife Juana, buy a riffle for himself and
pay education expenses for Coyotito.
Kino kills a ma when he is attacked in self-defense.
Kino savagely beats his wife up when she tries to throw Pearl back into the sea.
Kino clings to the pearl until their baby dies. His house is burned, Canoe destroyed.
Kino claims that the pearl has become his soul.
On the way to the capital he kills three men following them for the pearl.
All this is a sign of obsession
2. GREED
The news of Kinos pearl has stirred up evil intention from various people. Greed is
evil and has infected both the rich and the poor.
The doctors, merchants, priest and beggars all think of the pearl in monetary terms.
Prep By Mr. E. Sam Navaya
Page 30 of 36
Greed makes people in town to conduct acts of violence against Kino is attempting to
still the pearl. Blood is shed.
3. CORRUPTION
Corruption has fueled greed. Thus is seen in the lives of individuals and the society at
large.
The doctor is corrupted by his love of money and fine possession in silk robe. He sits
in his beautiful house sipping chocolate from a China cup while he refuses to treat
Coyotito, who has been stung by a scorpion. He does this because the baby is an
Indian and he says he not a veterinary. He later gives a hand to Kinos pearl.
4. RELIGION
Religion is portrayed negatively in the Novel. The priest who is supposed to be a strong
pillar and a role model seems corrupt and self-serving.
Kinos life has fallen apart even though he is a religious man. Juana has been offering a
protection prayer but little seems to have taken place.
Based on this religion in the story is not something to be trusted and counted on. It leads
to disappointment.
5. PRICE OF WISDOM
Juana seems to have the understanding of the impact of clinging to the pearl. She says It
will destroy us all and even our son.
This has come to pass because their house is burnt, Kinos canoe smashed and their son
Coyotito shot dead.
Juana Tomas too tries to save them from destruction. He says there is a devil in the
pearl. He advices Kino to sell it or throw it back into the ocean in order to pass on the
devil.

Juan believes that if Kino sells the Pearl he will buy a peace for himself but Kino refuses.
He clings to it.
Kino beat his wife for trying to throw the pearl back into the ocean. In the end Kino has
come to believe that both Juana and Juan were right.
Kino personally returns the pearl to the sea after the death of his son, his house burnt and
Cone smashed.
This is a terrible price to pay for Kinos acquiring wisdom.
6. IMPORTANCE OF THE FAMILY
The family is indicated as the only institution where one can find warmth. When Kino
seems to be troubled he finds warmth from his wife Juana.
Juana gives warmth to Kino in the following ways: by her presence to him, she nurses
Kinos wound when he gets attached.
Kino says when he gets rich, will marry his wife Juan through the church. All this
because he is satisfied.
Kino is accompanied by his family to the market to sell the pearl with high expectations.
Juana and Coyotito seem to enjoy Kinos protection as family head.
Juana, Kinos brother and his wife sympathizes what Kino pass through. He advices Kino
that he should not be cheated by the pearl buyers, when Kinos house is burnt, he offers
him accommodation.
The family song Kino hears also symbolizes the significance of the family. All in all
Kino enjoys the warmth and this shows that the family is the very important institution
ever.
7. WEALTH
The story shows that wealth has both advantages and disadvantages. He goodness is
that it brings joy and one is able to meet needs and fulfill family needs (obligations)

Kino feels that once he gets rich will be able to marry his wife through church and
send his son to school.
On the other hand wealth has challenges, for example; Kino has become center of
attraction. Various people plot to attack him and his family and get away with the
pearl.
Almost everybody wants to cheat Kino in order to get his pearl.
In the end his house is burnt to ashes, Canoe smashed and his son Coyotito is shot
dead all because of the Pearl.
Wealth brings both happiness and insecurity. To addition insecurity perhaps thats
why Kino says one of the item he will buy when he get rich is a rifle.
8. GOOD VERSUS EVIL
Family is good. It brings warmth and comfort one needs in difficult times.
Greed is evil. It makes people envious and filled with self-serving spirit. For
example the priest who thinks of church repair and the doctor who needs Paris and
furniture.
Love is good. It brings consolation of the mind is the best medicine in hard times.
For instance Kino beats up his wife because of the pearl, but in the end they
reconcile because of the love.
9. GENDER
Kino by virtue of being the man he becomes family head and Jun respects all
decisions made by Kino there good or bad. The same applies to Juan over
Apolonia.
Kino is ultimate speaker of the family and everyone should bow down to him.
10. PREMITIVE
The pearl has changed the man form civilized and to primitive one. He is scared and a
protective beast. He declares that everyone is his enemy and is afraid of everyone.
